In article <29u3mi$pvp@itu1.sun.ac.za> apj@beldin.sun.ac.za (Andries Dippenaar) writes:
>Wim van Dorst/Prof. Penninger (tgcpwd@rwb.urc.tue.nl) wrote:
>: Roger C. Pao writes:
>
>: >I can't do a colon operation like ":123,s/tic/tac/g" and expect it to
>: >substitute all occurrances of tic for tac starting from line 123 to where
>: >the cursor is currently.
>That is one of my greater irritations with elvis.

Well, it works if you include a dot ('.'), which stands for current line...
        :123,. s/tic/tac/g
But I do agree, I think elvis should do a little better job at emulating 
the "real" vi (whatever that is).  Which means that the example without the
dot should do the same thing as with the dot.

>: >So, anyone have a vi which is really vi compatible?
>Try to lay your hands on vim (Vi IMitation) by Bram Moolenaar.  The
>latest version is 1.27 and it is the ultimate best vi implementation
>I've yet come across.  It has several extentions like multi-level undo,
>filename completion on the command line, stream, interactive marking of
>line and column blocks, history for the command line and much much more.

Yeah, well, and I had some real problems with vim as well.  It wouldn't be
so bad, but I couldn't get some of the "extensions" to be turned off by 
using a /etc/exrc file, such as writing backup files (despite me telling it
not to write them in the first place).  Vim is better in some respects, but
it is much worse in other respects.

I have heard of xvi, but does anybody know about that one?

>: >P.S.: Please don't tell me to use emacs.  
>Wouldn't dream of doing that. :-)

I wouldn't even think of doing such a horrible thing to you :-)

Note, followups will go to comp.editors, since that is really where this
discussion belongs...

Scott
