From: jes@grendel.demon.co.uk (Jim Segrave)
Subject: Re: Linus Torvalds may be a just a persona created artificially!
Date: Wed, 20 Oct 1993 00:04:46 +0000

In article <10480@fs3.cam.nist.gov> mitchell@cam.nist.gov writes:
>In article <GTHAKER.93Oct14150718@trantor.atl.ge.com>, gthaker@atl.ge.com (Gautam H. Thaker) writes:
>|> 
>|> I have this theory that Linus Torvalds is not a real person at all!
>|> "Linus" is in fact a persona created (perhaps by a group of graduate
>|> students) to project this aura of superhuman.
>
>And who was it that placed those gif files at tsx-11 with photos of "Linus"?
>I suspect they were taken at a frat party and later used to propagate the
>myth of this persona "Linus".
>

No, I've used real science (TM) to prove that he's one person:
Using the techniques of counting word patterns to identify author's
that was pioneered in proving that Bacon wrote Shakespeare (or Shakespeare
wrote Bacon or whatever - anyway, that's beside the point) on the kernel
sources, some distinct patterns emerge:
The author uses as many '{' characters as he does '}'.
The same applies for '(' and ')'.
And even for the more arcane '/*' and '*/'.
He is inoridnately fond of punctuating with semicolons.
He is overly smitten with some of his early works and misses no 
opportunity to remind us of them, by including them in his later
derivative works.
His character development is somewhat weak - some good ideas - the
mysterious persons (deities perhaps?) known only as the 'swapper' and
the 'scheduler' suggest an attempt to inject some mysticism into a
deterministic world-view.
Plots tend towards the mind-numbingly complex.
The dialogue puts even James Joyce to shame - I find it almost impossible
to find who is meant to be speaking the quoted sections - they are all
attributed to the unseen 'printk'.
He seems to prefer a style in which multiple story lines - referred to
somewhat obsucrely as processes) are interwoven and progress concurrently.

So we can conclude that one anal-retentive personna with a seriously
disturbed concept of modern life wrote every line of the kernel source,
probably gcc, X-windows etc. as well.

:-) for the humour impaired.






-- 
Jim Segrave        (Segrave Software Services jes@grendel.demon.co.uk)


